    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Because of an editing error, a front-page article yesterday about a Federal pollution complaint against the General Motors Corporation misstated the formula for the $45 million settlement. The company is to pay an $11 million civil fine. It will also spend $8.75 million on compensatory programs to reduce air pollution from other sources, a figure that could vary depending on the effectiveness of the company's recall of about 470,000 cars. The remaining cost, estimated to be at least $25 million, is for recalling the cars and repairing the problem.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Because of an editing error, a front-page article yesterday about a Federal pollution complaint against the General Motors Corporation misstated the formula for the $45 million settlement. The company is to pay an $11 million civil fine. It will also spend $8.75 million on compensatory programs to reduce air pollution from other sources, a figure that could vary depending on the effectiveness of the company's recall of about 470,000 cars. The remaining cost, estimated to be at least $25 million, is for recalling the cars and repairing the problem.</p>
        <p>Because of another editing error, the article referred inaccurately in some  editions to the pollutant involved. It is carbon monoxide, not carbon dioxide.</p>
      </block>
